11 An Act relating to technology; defining terms;
directing deployers to ensure social artificial
12 intelligence companions are not knowingly made
available to minors; permitting lawful access by
13 adults; directing deployers to implement protocols to
prioritize safety and well-being of users;
14 establishing civil penalties; granting the attorney
general rulemaking authority; providing for
15 noncodification; providing for codification; and
providing an effective date.
16
17
18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
20 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
21 The Legislature finds that:
22 1. Artificial intelligence systems designed to simulate
23 sustained interpersonal companionship or emotional attachment may
24
Req. No. 17208 Page 1

1 pres ent unique risks to minors due to their developmental
2 vulnerability to parasocial bonding;
3 2. The State of Oklahoma has a compelling interest in
4 protecting the health, safety, and well-being of minors; and
5 3. This act is narrowly tailored to restrict access by minors
6 to social AI companions while preserving lawful access by adults and
7 general conversational artificial intelligence systems.
8 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 10 of Title 75A, unless there is
10 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 As used in this act:
12 1. "Artificial intelligence" means engineered or machine
13 learning-based system that varies in its level of autonomy and that
14 can, for explicit or implicit objectives, infer from the input it
15 receives how to generate outputs that can influence physical or
16 virtual environments.
17 2. "Social AI companion" means an artificial intelligence
18 system primarily designed or marketed to simulate sustained
19 interpersonal companionship and emotional attachment or romantic
20 interaction with a user as the system's core functionality. The term
21 "Social AI companion" does not include:
22 a. a system used solely for customer service, business
23 operations, productivity, analysis related to source
24
Req. No. 17208 Page 2

1 information, internal purposes, research purposes, or
2 technical assistance,
3 b. a stand-alone consumer electronic device that
4 incorporates a speaker or voice or text command interface,
5 acts as a virtual assistant, and does not sustain a
6 relationship across multiple interactions and generate
7 outputs intended to create emotional attachment with the
8 user,
9 c. a search engine feature that provides information in
10 response to user queries and is not designed or marketed
11 to simulate companionship,
12 d. a system designed to provide outputs relating to a
13 narrow and discrete functional topic and not primarily
14 intended to simulate interpersonal companionship, or
15 e. a system that is not primarily designed or marketed
16 for companionship where the developer does not control the
17 specific deployment context in which the system interacts
18 with end users.
19 3. "Deployer" means any person, partnership, corporation, or
20 governmental entity that operates, controls, or makes available a
21 social AI companion to users in this state. A deployer does not
22 include a mobile application store, search engine, internet service
23 provider, or provider of general-purpose artificial intelligence
24
Req. No. 17208 Page 3

1 mode ls solely because such entity provides access to, hosts, or
2 transmits a system developed or controlled by another person.
3 4. "Minor" means a person who is under eighteen (18) years of
4 age.
5 5. "User" means a person who interacts with a social AI
6 companion.
7 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 11 of Title 75A, unless there is
9 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 A. Each deployer:
11 1. Shall not knowingly, or under circumstances where the
12 deployer reasonably should know, make a social AI companion
13 available to a minor; and
14 2. Shall implement reasonable measures designed to prevent
15 minors from accessing a social AI companion.
16 B. Nothing in this section shall be construed to restrict
17 lawful access to such systems by adults.
18 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 12 of Title 75A, unless there is
20 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A deployer shall adopt a protocol for a social AI companion
22 to respond to user prompts indicating suicidal ideation or
23 threats of self-harm that includes, but is not limited to,
24 making reasonable efforts to provide a response to the user
Req. No. 17208 Page 4

1 that refers them to crisis service providers such as a suicide
2 hotline, crisis text line, or other appropriate crisis
3 services.
4 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 13 of Title 75A, unless there is
6 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. Any deployer that violates this act shall be subject to an
8 injunction and disgorgement of profits directly attributable to the
9 violation of this act, and shall be liable for a civil penalty of
10 not more than Two Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($2,500.00) for each
11 violation or Seven Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($7,500.00) for
12 each intentional violation, which shall be assessed and recovered in
13 a civil action brought by the Attorney General. Each day a
14 violation continues constitutes a separate violation.
15 B. The Attorney General may promulgate any rules necessary to
16 enforce the provisions of this act.
17 SECTION 6. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
